I would be lying if I said I feel as confident as I look - the truth is I’m not where I want to be and instead of getting closer to my goals, the past few months I’ve strayed further away from them. 

The tiredness from having a bubba that doesn’t like to sleep had finally caught up with me and I’ve lacked serious motivation. My training, meals and sleep have been irregular and instead I’ve found myself not moving much at all and craving sugary things for a quick, energy spike. 

I had to remind myself of what I would say to a client - our bodies can go through seasons and sometimes life gets in the way of our goals. Instead of dwelling or putting yourself down, focus on what you CAN do now.

So I’ve picked myself back up, apologised to my body for thinking negatively about it and I’m back on it 👊🏽 Just incase anyone else is feeling pretty down about where they are right now - you have the power to change your circumstances… start taking the necessary steps 🤎

✨One-pot Cajun chicken✨ I make this simple dish weekly and there’s enough to have for lunch the next day too 🙌🏽

Preheat the oven to 400F and season the chicken drumsticks with olive oil, Cajun, garlic, chilli powder, paprika, salt, black pepper.

Chop up some onions and peppers nice and chunky and add them to an oven proof dish along with the chicken. Cook for around 35 - 40 mins. 

Rinse your rice and chop up some tomatoes! Add the tomatoes, 1 cup of rice and 2 cup boiling water to the dish. Cover with foil and cook for another 20mins.

Add some spinach and dollops of natural yoghurt and voila! ✨

I’ve been working on me 🤍

Since entering this new chapter in my life, I’ve never felt more pressure to try and juggle everything. I’ve struggled to find the right balance, and noticed that if I put all my energy into one aspect of my life, other parts take a back seat. But the truth is - you can’t put 100% into everything all the time, and that’s okay. 

So here’s to the women that push through during the difficult chapters, who still try to find the time to work on themselves, prioritise their family, juggle a work/life balance and try to find the joy in every season, including the good, the bad and the challenging ones. Life will always bring waves, here’s to the women that learn to ride them every single day… no matter how that might look.

Tag a mama or mama-to-be! ✨ *this series is also good for anyone getting back into or just starting to workout! 

Now I’m going to be honest - pre-pregnancy I rarely warmed up before working out, my body was just ready to go! And now, well let’s just say the structural and hormonal changes that happen during pregnancy don’t just disappear as soon as you’re postpartum.

Your body feels different and it’s going to be a journey to regain the strength and flexibility you once had, so warming up is a MUST to prevent injury and allow your body a chance to settle in on the workout that’s ahead of you. I like to start off on the treadmill or stair-master followed by stretches like these. Save this post and try this lower body warm up next time!

It’s not been easy 😮‍💨 but at 8 months postpartum I’m feeling the best I have!! 

As a new mum I totally get how easy it is to neglect our own well-being, but I’m here to tell you your health is a priority. When you put everyone else’s needs above your own, you put yourself at risk for not only physical but also mental health issues. 

Gone are the days where we viewed self-care as selfish or a luxury, it’s a necessity and you deserve to show up as your best self.

Tag a mama or mama-to-be! ✨ Let me start by saying I actually had this, so I’m sharing from experience! While my gap was only 2 fingers wide at the belly button, it was extremely deep! I received physical therapy to help with this and had to be extremely cautious with what exercises I was doing. If you think you might have diastasis recti - please get it checked before starting your fitness routine! 

Diastasis recti is where the two parts of the rectus abdominis (the abdominal muscles) separate during pregnancy. Fortunately, there’s a simple way to check for this at home. Here’s how it’s done: 

1. Lie flat on your back with your knees bent.
2. Place your fingers on your belly button, pointing towards your pelvis, and press down.
3. Lift your head up slightly while keeping your shoulders on the ground and tuck in your chin.
4. If you have diastasis recti, you will feel a gap between the muscles that is an inch wide (~ 2 fingers) or greater.

If you think you may have diastasis recti, it’s important to seek medical advice from your doctor or a healthcare professional. They can help provide you with proper treatment and advice on how to manage it. 🫶🏽

You’re more likely to skip this part of your workout, I get it! You’re tired, maybe you’ve exerted all your energy, but that’s exactly why cooling down is so important to promote a faster recovery and protect those muscles of yours. 

Now why foam roll? It’s a technique that helps to increase blood flow, pull toxins from your muscles, and reduce injury or soreness. It doesn’t have to take long - focus on the muscle group you just trained and even 5 mins can make a difference.

Why the compliment “You look like you’ve never had a baby, baby where” however well intentioned, can be more harmful than good. 

I feel like we become so focused on getting our pre-pregnancy body back, because according to society we look great as long as we don’t look like we’ve had a baby. And I’m going to be honest - getting my body back was my first thought when I began working out postpartum. 

But the reality is, our bodies have changed, even if it’s not easy-to-spot. It’s been stretched, gained marks and scars, carried and birthed. It isn’t the same body as before, and that’s okay. In fact, it isn’t just okay, it’s an absolute miracle and what an honour to go through the journey we have. 

So instead of focusing on getting our old body back or using the lack of physical proof that a woman has given birth as a compliment, let’s celebrate this new, strong, amazing, capable body of ours. 

I almost booked scar revision surgery to replace my rushed emergency c-section scar that is deep, dark and slightly raised. But swiftly cancelled when I thought, who is to say this isn’t beautiful? To me it represents the journey me and my sweet Asher went through and is so much more than just a scar or how it looks. So it will stay and I will admire it with appreciation. 

I hope you too are able to view your post-pregnancy marks with admiration, and know it’s okay to look like you’ve carried and it’s also totally okay to work on being the best version of you in this new body of yours.
